---
import PageLayout from '../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import HealthTable from '../components/HealthTable.astro';
import ServiceCard from '../components/ServiceCard.astro';
import { services } from '../data/services';
---

<PageLayout
  title="Getting Started Guide & Modular Architecture"
  description="Follow our practical 3-step setup to understand the architecture, configure, and launch your personal home server using Docker Compose."
>
  <div class="space-y-12">
    <!-- Intro Banner -->
    <section class="glass p-8 border border-accent/40 bg-gradient-to-br from-bg-surface via-bg-surface to-accent/5">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mt-0">⚡ How Our Modular Architecture Works</h2>
      <p class="text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-6">
        We believe in understanding your system: <strong>Architecture First, Then Implement.</strong> Instead of blind automation scripts that hide what is happening under the hood, our repository is structured into completely standalone, heavily commented application stacks inside the <code>stacks/</code> directory so you understand how ports, networks, and storage volumes work while building your cloud.
      </p>
      
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 font-sans not-prose">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-lg bg-bg border border-border">
          <span class="text-xs font-mono text-accent font-bold">STEP 01</span>
          <h3 class="font-bold text-text text-base mt-1">Prepare Storage</h3>
          <p class="text-xs text-text-muted mt-1">Create unified <code>/data</code> folders so all your media and downloads share a clean hierarchy.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-lg bg-bg border border-border">
          <span class="text-xs font-mono text-accent font-bold">STEP 02</span>
          <h3 class="font-bold text-text text-base mt-1">Configure .env</h3>
          <p class="text-xs text-text-muted mt-1">Copy <code>stacks/.env.example</code> to <code>stacks/.env</code> and set your user ID and passwords.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-lg bg-bg border border-border">
          <span class="text-xs font-mono text-accent font-bold">STEP 03</span>
          <h3 class="font-bold text-text text-base mt-1">Start & Learn</h3>
          <p class="text-xs text-text-muted mt-1">Navigate into any stack directory and run <code>docker compose up -d</code>!</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Step 1 Command -->
    <section>
      <h2>1. Clone Repository & Prepare Storage (`/data`)</h2>
      <p>
        First, clone this repository onto your home server. Then create your unified storage directory tree under <code>/data</code> (or any path you prefer) and assign ownership to your Linux user (`$USER`). This ensures all containers can read and write media cleanly without permission denied errors:
      </p>
      <CodeBlock
        title="bash — Repository Cloning & Storage Setup"
        code={`git clone https://github.com/Zamiul-rashid/Homelabbing.git\ncd Homelabbing\n\n# Create our standard directory tree for movies, TV, music, books, photos, and cloud storage\nsudo mkdir -p /data/media/{movies,tv,music,books,comics,photos} /data/downloads/{incomplete,complete} /data/nextcloud\n\n# Assign ownership to your current Linux user\nsudo chown -R $USER:$USER /data`}
      />
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl bg-blue-950/20 border border-blue-500/30 text-xs text-blue-200 not-prose mt-4">
        <strong>💡 Why `/data`?</strong> By keeping your media and download directories under the same parent folder path (`/data`), download clients like qBittorrent and organizers like Radarr can perform instantaneous, zero-copy hardlinks—saving hard disk space and CPU cycles!
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Step 2 Command -->
    <section>
      <h2>2. Configure Environment Variables (`stacks/.env`)</h2>
      <p>
        Every modular stack automatically pulls shared variables (like your timezone, database passwords, and user IDs) from a single central environment file inside <code>stacks/.env</code>. Copy the template and verify your user permissions using <code>id -u</code> and <code>id -g</code>:
      </p>
      <CodeBlock
        title="bash — Environment Configuration"
        code={`# Copy the documented environment template\ncp stacks/.env.example stacks/.env\n\n# Check your current Linux user ID and group ID (usually 1000)\nid -u\nid -g\n\n# Open stacks/.env in your favorite terminal editor to set your secure passwords\nnano stacks/.env`}
      />
    </section>

    <!-- Step 3 Command -->
    <section>
      <h2>3. Launch Your Chosen Stack</h2>
      <p>
        You do not need to boot everything at once! Move inside any modular application folder inside <code>stacks/</code> (such as <code>media-server/</code> or <code>book-reader/</code>) and start it in detached background mode:
      </p>
      <CodeBlock
        title="bash — Starting a Modular Stack"
        code={`cd stacks/media-server\ndocker compose up -d`}
      />
      
      <div class="terminal-window not-prose border border-border my-6">
        <div class="terminal-titlebar">
          <span class="text-xs font-mono text-text-muted">Terminal Output — docker compose up -d</span>
        </div>
        <div class="p-5 bg-terminal-bg font-mono text-xs text-terminal-text space-y-1">
          <p class="text-text-muted">[+] Running 2/2</p>
          <p class="text-success"> ✔ Network media-server_default   Created                            0.1s</p>
          <p class="text-success"> ✔ Container jellyfin               Started                            0.4s</p>
          <p class="pt-2 text-accent font-bold">✨ Jellyfin is now live! Open your browser right now:</p>
          <p class="font-bold">👉 http://YOUR_SERVER_IP:8096</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Explore Services Directory -->
    <section>
      <h2>4. Explore All Modular Stacks</h2>
      <p>
        Want to inspect the exact architectural comments or read the detailed onboarding walkthrough for a specific service? Click any card below:
      </p>
      
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 not-prose my-8">
        {services.map((s) => (
          <ServiceCard service={s} />
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Health table -->
    <section>
      <h2>5. Health Checking Across All Ports</h2>
      <p>
        To verify that all containers are running cleanly without error loops or database connection timeouts, run our diagnostic health checker from the repository root at any time:
      </p>
      <CodeBlock
        title="bash — Automated Health Diagnostics"
        code={`./helpers/check-health.sh`}
      />
      <HealthTable />
    </section>
  </div>
</PageLayout>
